description:
TL;DR: The {{MongoClient}} class has a {{codec_options}} property, which is used as the default {{CodecOptions}} for all operations using that client unless explicitly stated otherwise. There is currently no way for the user to change two properties of {{MongoClient.codec_options}}, namely {{unicode_decode_error_handler}} and {{tzinfo}}, since they have not been added to {{pymongo.common.VALIDATORS}}.

Going into more details:

- the {{codec_options}} property of {{MongoClient}} is set on [line 377|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-python-driver/blob/master/pymongo/mongo_client.py#L377], which takes the value of {{options.codec_options}}. {{options}} itself is a {{ClientOptions}} object which was created on [line 363|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-python-driver/blob/master/pymongo/mongo_client.py#L363].

- within the {{ClientOptions}} class, the {{codec_options}} property is set on [line 128|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-python-driver/blob/master/pymongo/client_options.py#L128], which calls the {{bson.codec_options._parse_codec_options}} method, with the input being the {{options}} parameter of the constructor. {{_parse_codec_options}} reads the following properties of {{options}} to  to create a customized {{CodecOptions}} object:
-* {{document_class}}
-* {{tz_aware}}
-* {{uuidrepresentation}}
-* {{unicode_decode_error_handler}}
-* {{tzinfo}}

- within the context of the {{MongoClient}} constructor, the value of that parameter is given by the {{opts}} variable, which is a dictionary of validated client options. However, this {{opts}} variable *cannot* contain two of the properties listed above, since neither {{unicode_decode_error_handler}} nor {{tzinfo}} are part of {{pymongo.common.VALIDATORS}}.

In PYTHON-767 we added support for a strict_date option. The implementation matches the behavior of MongoDB 2.6 era mongoexport. That is, it outputs ISO-8601 format for post-epoch dates and $numberLong for pre-epoch dates.

With the release of MongoDB 3.0, [mongoexport started using ISO-8601 output for pre-epoch dates as well|https://jira.mongodb.org/browse/SERVER-15275?focusedCommentId=1269085&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels:comment-tabpanel#comment-1269085]. However, [it uses $numberLong for maxDate|https://jira.mongodb.org/browse/TOOLS-1179].

Let's replace the unreleased strict_date boolean with a datetime_representation option, configured with an enum, and use that setting for all datetime output. Something like:

{noformat}
class DatetimeRepresentation:
    # {$date: <int64>}
    LEGACY = 0
    # {$date: {$numberLong: <int64>}}
    NUMBERLONG = 1
    # {$date: <ISO-8601>}
    ISO8601 = 2
{noformat}

Currently the documentation either can't build, can't test, or both under python 3.x. In the v2.9 branch the source needs to run through 2to3 before the docs are built. In v2.9 and master the documentation has to be updated to be python 3.x compatible. This mostly appears to involve changing lines like:

{noformat}
print foo
{noformat}

to

{noformat}
print(foo)
{noformat}

Before Python 3.2, the ssl module did not distinguish between timeouts and other ssl exceptions. See https://bugs.python.org/issue10272.

In CPython 2.6 and 2.7 the ssl module raises a generic ssl.SSLError on socket timeouts. The error has a single attribute, {{message}}, set to 'The read operation timed out'.

One improvement would be:
{code:python}
def _raise_connection_failure(address, error):
    """Convert a socket.error to ConnectionFailure and raise it."""
    host, port = address
    # If connecting to a Unix socket, port will be None.
    if port is not None:
        msg = '%s:%d: %s' % (host, port, error)
    else:
        msg = '%s: %s' % (host, error)
    if isinstance(error, socket.timeout):
        raise NetworkTimeout(msg)
    elif isinstance(error, SSLError) and 'timed out' in error.message:
        raise NetworkTimeout(msg)
    else:
        raise AutoReconnect(msg)
{code}

Research needs to be done to make sure this is portable on supported versions of CPython, PyPy, and PyPy3.

As there's a behavioral change in the [{{mongo_client}}|https://api.mongodb.com/python/3.0/api/pymongo/mongo_client.html#module-pymongo.mongo_client] module for {{3.0}} in which the {{MongoClient}} object will not validate a connection before performing an operation I think it may be a good idea to add the "Changed in version 3.0" section before the section quoted below.

{quote}
The host parameter can be a full mongodb URI, in addition to a simple hostname.
{quote}

For some reason the following code raises a Timeout instead of doing the upsert when it gets to the bulk.execute() line. If we remove the sleep command it all works. If we run the code outside of a greenlet it all works. If I remove the bulk.execute() command it doesn't insert the data obviously, but it doesn't cause the error. It's some combination of both gevent and pymongo that is causing this. The reason for the sleep command is that it represents an action that takes a certain amount of processing, which in the code I first noticed this problem in was marshalling data.

{code:python}
from gevent import monkey
monkey.patch_all()
from pymongo import MongoClient

import datetime
import time
import gevent

class Streamer(gevent.Greenlet):
    def run(self):
        mongodb = MongoClient('hostname', 27017)
        mongodb.admin.authenticate('user', 'pass')
        gevent.sleep(1)
        db = mongodb['mydb']['mycollection']
        bulk = db.initialize_unordered_bulk_op()
        bulk.find(
            {'CreatedDate': '2016-11-12'},
        ).upsert().update(
            {
                '$set': {'UpdateTime': datetime.datetime.utcnow()},
                '$setOnInsert': {
                    'CreatedDate': '2016-11-12',
                }
            }
        )
        bulk.execute()

streamer = Streamer()
streamer.start()
time.sleep(1)
streamer.join()
time.sleep(60)
{code}
